# Release Notes Structure & Style Guide

## Core Philosophy

Release notes are for users, not engineers. Every entry should answer:
**"What changed, why does it matter to me, and do I need to do anything?"**

Write for the person scanning on a Monday morning before a deployment — not the person who built the feature. Always link to existing documentation rather than re-explaining concepts inline.

---

## Document Structure

Release notes are organized by **Month + Year**, newest first. Within each month, use these sections in order:

```
## Month YYYY               ← e.g. ## February 2026

### New Features & Enhancements
### Feature Improvements
### Bug Fixes & Improvements
### Fixed Issues
### ⚠️ Breaking Changes      ← only if present
### Deprecations             ← only if present
```

Omit sections that have no entries. Never include an empty section.

---

## Month Heading

```markdown
## February 2026
```

- **Month and year only** — no version numbers, no ISO dates
- The heading becomes the anchor link: `#february-2026`
- Write the month in full (`February`, not `Feb`)
- Newest month at the top of the file

If a specific component has a version worth calling out, it goes inside the section body as a sub-label, never in the top-level heading:

```markdown
### New Features & Enhancements

- **IAC Server: Version 1.126:** One or more sentences about this specific version and what customers get.
```

---

## Entry Format

Put the **bold title**, a **colon**, and the **description on the same line** (one line per entry is typical; wrap in the editor if needed). Do not put a blank line between the title and the body.

Prefix each entry with a **list marker** (`- `) under the month subsection. The [Harness Release Notes](/release-notes) landing page summarizer only collects bulleted lines; a recent `date` in frontmatter can still show a stub card if bullets are missing, but bullets are required for real summaries.

**With documentation link (link in the title or opening clause):**
```markdown
- **Feature Name [Docs](/docs/path/to/relevant-page):** One or two sentences describing the user-facing change and its benefit.
```

**Without documentation link:**
```markdown
- **Feature Name:** One or two sentences describing the user-facing change and its benefit.
```

**Example (real pattern):**
```markdown
- **Custom Template Library as a full HTL mirror:** Custom Template Library can be configured as a one-time full mirror of the official Harness Template Library repository.
```

**With an issue ID (for bug fixes):** Prefer a single line. If there is no extra prose beyond the ticket, you can keep the summary and ID tight:

```markdown
**Short description of what was fixed (IssueCode-1234):** Optional extra sentence if needed.
```

Or when the entry is only a one-liner:

```markdown
**Short description of what was fixed.** (IssueCode-1234)
```

### Linking to docs

Always prefer linking to an existing doc page over explaining a concept inline. Use the short internal path format:

```markdown
[Docs](/docs/infra-as-code-management/platform-integrations/platform/iacm-mcp)
```

- Link to the most specific relevant page (a specific feature page, not the product root)
- If a new feature doesn't have a doc yet, don't fabricate a link — omit the `[Docs](…)` link and add one once the doc exists
- For breaking changes or migrations, link to a dedicated migration guide if one exists

---

## Entry Writing Rules

### Titles

| ✅ Do | ❌ Don't |
|---|---|
| `MCP Server` | `INFRA-4421: Added MCP support` |
| `Terragrunt (Beta)` | `Terragrunt support improvements` |
| `Pipeline execution retry` | `Fixed bug in pipeline` |
| `OPA policy filtering per environment` | `Policy improvements` |

- Use the **product or feature name** as the bold title
- Append a lifecycle label in the title when relevant: `Feature Name (Beta)`, `Feature Name (Early Access)`, `Feature Name (GA)`
- No ticket numbers in titles — issue IDs belong in the body or parenthetically on bug fix lines

### Body copy

- Put the description on the **same line** as the bold title, immediately after the colon (no blank line between title and body)
- Lead with the **user-facing outcome**, not the implementation
- One to two sentences is the norm; go longer only if context is genuinely needed
- If the change requires user action, start with **Action required:**
- Avoid restating what's already in the title — add new information
- Plain language — if you need a technical term, it should already be defined in the linked doc

---

## Category Definitions

| Section | Use for |
|---|---|
| **New Features & Enhancements** | Capabilities that did not exist before |
| **Feature Improvements** | Meaningful upgrades to existing features (performance, UX, expanded scope) |
| **Bug Fixes & Improvements** | Resolved defects and minor behavioural corrections |
| **Fixed Issues** | Specific tracked bugs with issue IDs |
| **⚠️ Breaking Changes** | Changes that require user action to maintain existing behaviour |
| **Deprecations** | Features being phased out, with timeline and migration path |

---

## Lifecycle Labels

Append to the feature name in the bold title:

| Label | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `(Early Access)` | Opt-in only, API/behaviour may change |
| `(Beta)` | Broadly available, still gathering feedback |
| `(GA)` | Generally Available — stable, fully supported |
| `(Deprecated)` | Supported but scheduled for removal |

Example:
```markdown
- **Terragrunt (Beta) [Docs](/docs/infra-as-code-management/iac-stages/use-iac-stage/terragrunt):** Added a Terragrunt resources sidebar in the Resources tab during pipeline execution and OPA policy filtering per Terragrunt environment.
```

---

## Breaking Changes

When present, always appears as its own section and includes a migration path. Open with one line in the form `**Summary title:** First sentence…`, then add **`**Who is affected:**`**, **`**Action required:**`**, and before/after blocks on following lines as needed.

```markdown
### ⚠️ Breaking Changes

- **`trigger` field renamed to `triggerConfig` on the Pipeline Execution API [Migration Guide](/docs/path/to/migration):** The `trigger` field has been renamed to `triggerConfig` to align with the v2 configuration schema.

- **Who is affected:** Anyone calling `POST /pipelines/{id}/execute` directly.

**Before:** `{ "trigger": { "type": "manual" } }`
**After:** `{ "triggerConfig": { "type": "manual" } }`

The old field will continue to work until **April 2026**, then will be removed.
```

Always include:
- Who is affected
- Before/after examples when the change involves API shape or syntax
- A removal timeline
- A link to the migration guide or the most relevant doc

---

## Full Month Example

```markdown
## February 2026

### New Features & Enhancements

- **MCP Server [Docs](/docs/infra-as-code-management/platform-integrations/platform/iacm-mcp):** Introduced an MCP Server integration that allows AI assistants to interact with IACM resources directly, enabling natural language queries against infrastructure state.

- **Drift Detection for Terraform modules (Beta) [Docs](/docs/infra-as-code-management/iac-stages/drift-detection):** Drift detection now supports nested Terraform modules, surfacing configuration drift at the module level rather than only at the root.

---

### Feature Improvements

- **Terragrunt (Beta) [Docs](/docs/infra-as-code-management/iac-stages/use-iac-stage/terragrunt):** Added a Terragrunt resources sidebar in the Resources tab during pipeline execution and OPA policy filtering per Terragrunt environment.

---

### Fixed Issues

- **Fixed an issue where workspace list pagination would reset on filter change.** (IAC-3476)

- **Fixed incorrect status displayed during rollback when a prior run was still in progress.** (IAC-2281)
```

---

## What to Exclude

Never include:
- Semantic version numbers in the month heading
- Raw commit hashes or branch names
- Internal ticket numbers as primary identifiers (parenthetical on bug fixes only)
- Implementation details with no user-facing impact (refactors, test updates, CI changes)
- Vague entries: "Various stability improvements", "Minor bug fixes"
- Inline explanations of concepts that already have a doc page — link instead

---

## Quick Checklist

Before publishing, verify:

- [ ] Heading is `## Month YYYY` (e.g. `## February 2026`)
- [ ] Each entry is a list item: `- **Title:** description` (or `- **Title [Docs](/docs/...):** …`) on one line
- [ ] No ticket numbers in titles (only parenthetical on `Fixed Issues` lines)
- [ ] Lifecycle label included where feature is Beta / Early Access / GA
- [ ] Breaking changes section has who-is-affected, before/after, timeline, and migration link
- [ ] Deprecated features include removal date and link to migration path
- [ ] No vague entries or empty sections
- [ ] Newest month is at the top of the file
